cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  To recap,  
^c@2
^*bDouble^*n  or  ^*bRedouble^*n ^h show    the  1 step  response to the Asking Bid
^*bPass^*n                        ^h shows  the  2 step  response
^*bThe next bid up^*n             ^h shows  the  3 step  response, etc
@b^b@2
This is especially effective when the opponents  DOUBLE  the Asking Bid, because you actually GAIN space by this method.

Please bear in mind that PASS is  ^*bnot always an option^*n, (for example when partner has ALREADY passed over some interference which, as we'll see next week, can itself be an Asking Bid),

but  ^*bDouble^*n  or  ^*bRedouble^*n  will still be available in those circumstances to count as the 1 step response, and now 1 actual step would become the 2-step response  etc.

For example...
^c@2
1@C            -  (pass)    -    1@H    -    (pass)
1@S(Alpha)   -   (X)      -    ??? 

^bNow the alpha responses keep their normal steps but have different bids to represent them:

Re-Double ^f1 step   ^h shows ^j No @S support   and   0-3  controls  
Pass ^f2 steps  ^h shows ^j No @S support   and    4+  controls 
1NT  ^f3 steps  ^h shows ^j       @S support   and   0-3  controls    etc etc

^bso we've GAINED some space.
^b@2|
