^c@2
 1@C  -  1@H  -  2@D(Alpha)  -  (2@S)  -  ??? 
^b@2
^bOnce again the alpha responses keep their normal steps but have different bids to represent them:
^c@2
X    ^e 1 step ^h shows ^j       No @D Support   and   0-3   controls   
Pass ^e 2 steps^h shows ^j       No @D Support   and   4+    controls      
2NT  ^e 3 steps^h shows ^j             @D Support   and   0-3   controls      
3@C  ^e 4 steps^h shows ^j             @D Support   and   4+    controls
3@D  ^e 5 steps^h shows ^j GOOD @D Support   and   4      controls  
3@H  ^e 6 steps^h shows ^j GOOD @D Support   and   5      controls    etc
^b@2
So there we recovered ALL of the space lost due to the interference.
Sometimes we have still lost SOME space, but we're able to limit the damage to our seuqence, as in
^c@2
1@C             ^g   -    (pass)     -     1@H    -    (1@S) 
Pass(Gamma in @H)    -    (pass)     -     ??? 
^b@2
Here the Gamma responses keep their normal steps but have different bids to represent them:
^c@2
X    ^e 1 step ^h shows ^j     no Top Honour in @H 
1NT  ^e 2 steps ^h shows ^j     a 5-card suit with 1 Top Honour in @H, etc etc.
^b@2
So here, because partner's Pass was Asking, a Pass wasn't an option for us, (it would pass out the aution) so we can only reclaim 1 step with a double.

Bear in mind that we've actually gained a whole round of bidding because of partner being able to Pass to ask about our Hearts. so we're already ahead of the game.                                                 Let's look at an example hand|
