^*bkritter2:^*n  Why is it called   Relay Beta   rather than just   Beta?
 
  
|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at| It is just a name we gave it way back in the mists of time and it's stuck to differentiate it from any other time that beta is used.

A Relay in the next suit up (not counting the agreed trump suit) is ALWAYS available as Beta when we've just agreed trumps by means of an Asking Bid sequence.   Hence the name.

^^^^^c|fp|t-title|at|^*bMM:^*n            Up a bit Beta     v     Relay Beta |fp||at|                a difference in name only ^^^^|
at|^d@2^w@3
^*bMM:^*n   I find it clearer to think of it as  ^*bUp a bit Beta^*n  rather than  'Relay Beta'.    IMO the rules for where it falls are more complicated than implied by calling it a 'relay bid'.

For example Oliver is incorrect above where he says  "... Relay in the next suit up ...",  sometimes  ^*bUp a bit Beta^*n  will be in  No Trumps  and sometimes  No Trumps  will be skipped.  

( If the next  ^*bbid^*n  up is 3 No Trumps and if the agreed trump suit is a Major then 3 No Trumps is  ^*bUp a Bit Beta^*n.  If the agreed suit is a minor then  3 No Trumps  is a valid stopping point. )

The rules for  ^*bUp a bit Beta^*n  (Relay Beta) are scattered through out these chapters.  The Chapter on  Eta  is particularly pertinent.|
